re combine political, cultural, and historical analysis to explain how people in different parts of the world see the United States. They show that not all anti-Americanism can be blamed on U.S. foreign policy. America is disliked not just for what it does but also for what it is, and perceptions of both are profoundly shaped--and sometimes warped--by the domestic realities of the countries where anti-Americanism thrives. In addition to analyzing America's battered global reputation, these writers propose ways the United States and other countries can build better relations through greater understanding and respect.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh1 aAl-Marashi, Ibrahim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBudianta, Melani, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCriss, Nur Bilge, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEscalante-Gonzalbo, Fernando, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFarber, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFarber, David, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHadi al-Khalili, Abdul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHao, Yufan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMakhovskaya, Olga, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRomero, Federico, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShiraev, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSu, Lin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTenorio-Trillo, Mauricio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is 